A longitudinal study recruited 200 adults aged 60 to 69y to investigate the relation between indoor PM2.5 exposure and black carbon content in airway macrophages (AMBC). Subjects were visited for 5 times in the study. The dataset was saved in ‘ambc.csv’ with the following variables:

dat <- read.csv('Data/ambc.csv')
head(dat)
##   id male age time   pm ambc
## 1  1    1  67    1 14.4 0.91
## 2  1    1  67    2 13.1 1.10
## 3  1    1  67    3 14.7 0.94
## 4  1    1  67    4 17.9 1.22
## 5  1    1  67    5 17.3 1.52
## 6  2    1  65    1 18.7 0.95

Basic check of longitudinal data (lecture 5.2 Basic check of data)

Interaction plot and ICC

  1. Read the dataset into R. Plot the pattern of pattern of indoor PM2.5 and AMBC over time. Do you think AMBC are correlated within subjects?
## Correlation by visualization
require(lattice)
## Loading required package: lattice
with(dat,interaction.plot(time,id,pm, legend=F, lty=1, col=gray(0.7), 
                          xlab='follow up', ylab='Mean PM2.5', las=1))

with(dat,interaction.plot(time,id,ambc, legend=F, lty=1, col=gray(0.7),
                          xlab='follow up', ylab='AMBC', las=1))

#Can see patern in ambc not pm2.5

GEE (lecture 6)

Fitting GEE

  1. Fit a generalized estimating equation (GEE) model to predict AMBC by age, male, and PM2.5, by assuming independence, exchangeable, AR(1) and unstructured correlation structure.
## Fit GEE with different correlation structure; gaussian distribution coz continuous variables
library(geepack)
## Warning: package 'geepack' was built under R version 4.2.3
g.indp <- geeglm(ambc~male+age+pm, family=gaussian, id=id, corstr="independence", data=dat)
g.exch <- geeglm(ambc~male+age+pm, family=gaussian, id=id, corstr="exchangeable", data=dat)
g.ar1 <- geeglm(ambc~male+age+pm, family=gaussian, id=id, corstr="ar1", data=dat)
g.unstr <- geeglm(ambc~male+age+pm, family=gaussian, id=id, corstr="unstructured", data=dat)

Summarize above findings

  1. Compare the results in (a)-(i) from different methods.

All estimates are similar from different models, but the linear regression model is likely to have underestimated the uncertainty. (95%CI for linear regression is tighter coz it wrongly ignored the uncertainty of grouping)

Penalty regression (lecture 8)

Regression with traditional method (problem of multicollinearity)

LASSO regression

  1. Perform a LASSO regression and select the optimal λ by cross-validation method.
x <- model.matrix(ambc.5~-1+male+age+pm.1+pm.2+pm.3+pm.4+pm.5, data=data.wide)
y <- data.wide$ambc.5

require(glmnet)
## Loading required package: glmnet
## Warning: package 'glmnet' was built under R version 4.2.3
## Loaded glmnet 4.1-7
lasso.cv <- cv.glmnet(x,y,alpha=1)
plot(lasso.cv)

lambda.cv <- lasso.cv$lambda.min

## lambda if mininum is used
lasso.opt <- glmnet(x, y, alpha=1, lambda=lambda.cv)
coef(lasso.opt)
## 8 x 1 sparse Matrix of class "dgCMatrix"
